2ms / 128 = 15.625µs between RAS-only refreshes. 63.555765µs / 15.625µs = 4.06756896 times per line,
or "4 refresh cycles per horizontal line".
As the VDP fetches 8 bytes per 7 charcter cells, I have 4 x 500ns slots left over per line.
So I can use those 4 spare slots to perform a RAS-only refresh using counter taps.
128 rows / 4 per line = 32 lines. 32 lines x 63.5µs = 2.032µs (a 'hair' over spec.)
Needs 2 x 74LS157 (4x 2:1 Mux) to switch to the Refresh Address. And RAS-only logic (suppress CAS.)
Use 4 x 74LS157 to select the 14-bit Address Source.
Use 2 x 74LS157 to multiplex the low and high address halves.
CPU Path: Use a 74LS245 Octal Bus Transceiver, enable during CPU cycles, set direction from R/W.

Always: fetch a byte at 1.02 MHz bus-rate: 36 bytes per 256 px (use 4 extra cycles for refresh.)
APA modes: bypass the character ROM, load from latch to latch (cost: 2 x 74LS157 2:1 MUX)

Half-width mode:
• very useful for a 4K machine (1.5K VRAM -> 2K free for BASIC)
• remap address (MUX) to load the same byte twice; suppress loading into shifter; halve shifter clock.
• scan each vertical line twice; ignore bottom bit

74LS propagation delays ~15ns:
T=0ns:  Address Mux selects Row Address.
T=25ns: RAS falls. (Row is latched).
T=55ns: Address Mux selects Column Address. Row Address Hold (tRAH) is met. 
T=85ns: CAS falls. (Column is latched).
T=275ns: Data becomes valid (based on tRAC=250ns).
T=350ns: Data is latched by the CPU or VDP. RAS/CAS both return High.
T=500ns: Slot ends. This leaves 150ns for RAS Precharge (tRP), exceeding the required 100ns.

