To get a "broadcast-legal" NTSC signal in 1977 without a dedicated encoder chip,
you use a Passive Resistor Summer followed by a 2N3904 Transistor Emitter-Follower.

NTSC composite video is a 1.0V Peak-to-Peak signal into a 75Ω load. The "correct" voltages are:
• Sync: 0V (The "floor")
• Blanking/Black: 0.3V (The "pedestal")
• White: 1.0V
• Color Burst: A 0.3V p-p oscillation centered on the 0.3V blanking level.

Signal	        Logic State	Resistor (Approx)	Resulting Effect
Sync (H+V)	    Low (0V)	Direct/Diodes	Pulls the signal to 0.0V.
Blanking	    High (5V)	1kΩ	            Sets the "Black" level at ~0.3V.
Video Pixels	High (5V)	470Ω	        Adds ~0.7V on top of Black (~1.0V White).
Color Burst	    3.58MHz	    2.2kΩ	        "Injects" a small 0.3V wiggle onto the Black level.

The "Sync" Floor:
You use a 74LS05 (Open Collector) or a diode-OR gate.
When Sync is active, it physically shorts the video line to ground (0V).
The "Luma" Ladder:
Connect your Blanking signal (0V during SYNC) through a 1kΩ resistor to the "Mixing Node."
Connect your Pixel Data through a 470Ω resistor to the same node (0V during HBlank)
The "Chroma" Injection:
Take your 3.58MHz Phase Tap (from your 74LS151).
AND it with your Colorburst Enable signal using a 74LS08.
Feed that through a 2.2kΩ resistor into the mixing node.

3. The 2N3904 Output Stage (The "Buffer")
The mixing node has high impedance and cannot drive a 75Ω TV cable directly. You must use a NPN Transistor (2N3904):
Collector: Tied to +5V.
Base: Connected to your Mixing Node.
Emitter: This is your Video Out. Connect it to the RCA jack through a 75Ω resistor (to match the cable impedance) and a 100µF electrolytic capacitor (to block DC).

Look at Sinclair ZX80 and Apple II for reference.

The "TTL Low" isn't 0.0V
A 74LS chip (like your 166 Shifter or 151 Mux) doesn't output 0V when it's "Low." According to the 1977 data sheets:
V_OL (Typical): 0.35V
V_OL (Maximum): 0.50V

Using a second 2N3904 as a sync switch:
Collector: Connect this directly to your Mixing Node (the base of your output transistor).
Emitter: Tie this to System Ground.
Base: Connect this to your Sync Signal through a 1kΩ to 4.7kΩ resistor
During Active Video (Sync = LOW): The transistor is "Cut Off." It acts like an open circuit with very high impedance.
During Sync (Sync = HIGH): The transistor "Saturates." It becomes a low-resistance path (0.1V to 0.2V) directly to ground.
It "short-circuits" the entire resistor ladder. No matter what the other 74LS chips are outputting,
the mixing node is dragged down to the "Sync Tip" level.

In 1977, the "lazy" engineering approach — holding Blank High and letting Sync override it —
was the industry standard. It saves you at least one 74LS08 (AND) or 74LS02 (NOR) gate in your timing chain.

Front Porch: Blank = HIGH, Sync = LOW. (Mixing node sits at 0.3V Black).
Sync Pulse: Blank = HIGH, Sync = HIGH. (Transistor saturates, node drops to 0.1V Sync Tip).
Back Porch: Blank = HIGH, Sync = LOW. (Node returns to 0.3V Black).
Active Video: Blank = LOW, Sync = LOW. (Node is controlled by Pixel/Palette resistors).



Simplified BASIC

• variables above program (LET, DIM)
• basic stack on the 6502 stack
• heap top-down below video RAM (Strings, PROC-LOCALs)
• no local arrays, no redim
• PROC frames go in the HEAP (treated "as if" they're strings: chained 254-byte segments)
• LOCAL vars are appended to the tail PROC frame (Simple to undo: walk segments, mark free)
• Heap management: always allocate a new string (up to 254 bytes + length + refs)
• Heap management: when out of space, collect some garbage (move live strings upwards until enough room)
• Heap management: empty segments have length=0 followed by actual length (min segment is 2 bytes)
• Strings only allocate a segment if non-empty

BASIC Line Search

• SLOW version: lines start with <255><line.lo><line.hi><prevlen><thislen> (5 bytes)
• Walk forwards: LDY #3; .loop LDA (Ptr,Y); CLC; ADC Ptr; STA Ptr; BCS inc_hi; CMP (Ptr),X=0; BNE loop; check high byte ...
• Walk backward: LDY #2; .loop LDA (Ptr,Y); SEC; SBC Ptr; STA Ptr; BCC dec_hi; CMP (Ptr),X=0; BNE loop; check high byte ...
• The 255 sentinel is the LINE opcode

BASIC Line Index?

• Costs 4 bytes per line: <line.lo><line.hi><addr.lo><addr.hi> (4 bytes)  [costs 3 bytes per line]
• BASIC program duplicates: <255><line.lo><line.hi> (3 bytes)
• BASIC program without index: <255><line.lo><line.hi><len> (4 bytes)

BASIC Variable Index?

• SLOW version: inline all var names
• append HEAP Vars as DIM'd/assigned
• link-list all vars that start with the same letter
• keep 52 head pointers (104 bytes) in System Workspace

Slowness comes from:
  (a) searching the link-list for a matching var name
  (b) comparing var names character by character

• INDIRECT version:
  • convert all var names to indices into slot-arrays
    • <VAR1> or <VAR2><num> or <VAR3><num.lo><num.hi>
    • 52 x <VAR1> opcodes so single-letter vars remain 1 byte
  • dynamically allocate string and arrays, but pre-allocate numbers
  • doesn't actually cost any more memory (vs inline-name + var-heap-name)
  • keep root pointers to each table (tables move as the program is edited) [12*2=24]
  • runtime values can be in separate arrays (2 x number of root pointers)  [12*2*2=48]

    Numbers:
        <numL>{<num[5]><name[1]>}      - 1 ref -> 6 bytes (up to 52)                            [7]
    <num2.L/H>{<num[5]><name-ptr[2]>}  - 2 ref -> 7 bytes (up to 256) -> <len><name> NAME-HEAP  [10+name]
    <numN.L/H>{<num[5]><name-ptr[2]>}  - 3 ref -> 7 bytes (above 256) -> <len><name> NAME-HEAP  [11+name]

    Strings:
        <numL$>{<str-ptr[2]><name[1]>}      - 1 ref -> 3 bytes (up to 52)                             [4]
    <num2$.L/H>{<str-ptr[2]><name-ptr[2]>}  - 2 ref -> 4 bytes (up to 256) -> <len><name> NAME-HEAP   [7+name]
    <numN$.L/H>{<str-ptr[2]><name-ptr[2]>}  - 3 ref -> 4 bytes (above 256) -> <len><name> NAME-HEAP   [8+name]
    When assigned: \-> <len><string> in STR-HEAP

    Arrays:
        <numLA>{<arr-ptr[2]><name[1]>}      - 1 ref -> 3 bytes (up to 52)                             [4]
    <num2A.L/H>{<arr-ptr[2]><name-ptr[2]>}  - 2 ref -> 4 bytes (up to 256) -> <len><name> NAME-HEAP   [7+name]
    <numNA.L/H>{<arr-ptr[2]><name-ptr[2]>}  - 3 ref -> 4 bytes (above 256) -> <len><name> NAME-HEAP   [8+name]
    When assigned: \-> <size[2]><ndim>{<dim[2]>}{slots[5]} in BIG-HEAP

    String Arrays: (as above, replace slots[5] with slots[2])

